Month and Day, 2023
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
A capacitor is made of two concentric conducting spherical shells of radii
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

, that are maintained at a potential difference 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 , with the external shell being grounded.
 The origin of the coordinate system is the center of the two spheres.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Using Laplace equation, find the potential for any point in the region between
 the two conducting shells.
 Express your answer in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and the coordinates you choose.
 Don’t forget to justify your assumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Assuming that 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $b=2a$
\end_inset


\series default
, find the electric field in the region between the two shells.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Using general boundary conditions, find the total charge induced on each
 shell.
 Verify your answer using Green’s reciprocity, and assume 
\begin_inset Formula $b=2a$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Calculate the capacitance of this system if 
\begin_inset Formula $a=10$
\end_inset

 cm.
 Give both the formula and the numerical value.
 Use the general formula 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}=C_{ij}V_{j}$
\end_inset

 (p140 in Zangwill) and 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $b=2a$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
The center of the larger sphere is now shifted by a small displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

 along the z-axis: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}=s\hat{\mathbf{z}}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $𝑠≪𝑎$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming that the potential difference 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

  between the two spheres is maintained constant by a battery 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left|V_{0}^{\prime}\right|=\left|V_{0}\right|=\left|V_{b}-V_{a}\right|\right)$
\end_inset

, show that the distortion in the electric field between the conductors
 created by this displacement will induce a charge on the surface of the
 inner shell that is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma\left(\theta\right)=\epsilon_{0}\frac{abV_{0}}{b-a}\left[\frac{1}{a^{2}}-\frac{3s}{b^{3}-a^{3}}\cos\theta\right]
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent

\series bold
Sol.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Laplace equation is a linear PDE, thus, the superposition principle holds.
 Now, with this in mind, we can transform the problem as the sum/superposition
 of the following two problems:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
For the inner shell, we want to find the potential outside the sphere, assuming
 that the potential on the sphere is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
For the outer shell, we want to find the potential inside the sphere, assuming
 the potential is 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{b}$
\end_inset

 on the surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
\begin_inset CommandInset include
LatexCommand input
filename "/Users/emmanuelflores/Downloads/Figure.tex"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Now, with this in mind let's move on with the calculations.
 Because we have spherical symmetry is convenient to write the Laplacian
 operator in spherical coordinates, which is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla^{2}\square=\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left(r^{2}\frac{\partial\square}{\partial r}\right)+\frac{1}{r^{2}\sin\theta}\frac{\partial}{\partial\theta}\left(\sin\theta\frac{\partial\square}{\partial\theta}\right)+\frac{1}{r^{2}\sin^{2}\theta}\frac{\partial^{2}\square}{\partial\varphi^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

now, because of the symmetry, is clear that the solution doesn't depend
 on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 variable, i.e, we have asymuthal symmetry, and in this case the previous
 operator reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla^{2}\square=\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left(r^{2}\frac{\partial\square}{\partial r}\right)+\frac{1}{r^{2}\sin\theta}\frac{\partial}{\partial\theta}\left(\sin\theta\frac{\partial\square}{\partial\theta}\right),
\]

\end_inset

now, the problem we want to solve is given by the following PDE 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}V=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $V=V\left(r,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, which can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left(r^{2}\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}\right)+\frac{1}{r^{2}\sin\theta}\frac{\partial}{\partial\theta}\left(\sin\theta\frac{\partial V}{\partial\theta}\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset

now, using separation or variables, we can decompose the previous equation
 into to ODE, one for each variable, and then solve them separately, which
 will give us the following general solution 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(r,\theta\right)=\sum_{l=0}^{\infty}\left(\alpha_{l}r^{l}+\frac{\beta_{l}}{r^{l+1}}\right)P_{l}\left(\cos\theta\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{l},\beta_{l}$
\end_inset

 are determined by the boundary conditions.
 Now, for the first problem, we have the following boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(a,\theta\right)=V_{a},
\]

\end_inset

and using the general solution we can see that the term with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{l}$
\end_inset

 must vanish, and here's the reason, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{l}\neq0$
\end_inset

 then this implies that the potential will not go to zero as 
\begin_inset Formula $r\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, which is not physically admisible, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{l}=0,\forall l$
\end_inset

, thus the solution will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(r,\theta\right)=\sum_{l=0}^{\infty}\frac{\beta_{l}}{r^{l+1}}P_{l}\left(\cos\theta\right),
\]

\end_inset

and using the boundary condition we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(a,\theta\right)=\sum_{l=0}^{\infty}\frac{\beta_{l}}{a^{l+1}}P_{l}\left(\cos\theta\right)=V_{a},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
For this case we have...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Now using Green's reciproity we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Now, let's calculate the capacitance...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Finally...
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
For this part of the problem, we have the configuration given by the following
 figure:
\begin_inset CommandInset include
LatexCommand input
filename "LA3P4.tex"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And as the problem suggest, first, we're going to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{2}\approx b+s\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset

and, in order to prove that, we are going to use the law of cosines, which
 states the following 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{3}^{2}=\alpha_{1}^{2}+\alpha_{2}^{2}-2\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}\cos\gamma,
\]

\end_inset

but in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}=s$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}=r_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{3}=b$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\theta$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b^{2}=s^{2}+r_{2}^{2}-2sr_{2}\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset

but because 
\begin_inset Formula $s\ll r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}<r_{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $s\ll r_{2}$
\end_inset

, and this implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b^{2}\approx r_{2}^{2}-2sr_{2}\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset

and now, let's play a little bit with the math and write the rhs of the
 previous equation as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b^{2}\approx r_{2}^{2}\left(1-\frac{2s}{r_{2}}\cos\theta\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies b\approx r_{2}\sqrt{1-\frac{2s}{r_{2}}\cos\theta},
\]

\end_inset

and, if we rename 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{2s}{r_{2}}\cos\theta$
\end_inset

, we can Taylor expand the root as follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{1-x}\approx1-\frac{x}{2}+\mathcal{O}\left(x^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

then, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\approx r_{2}\left(1-\frac{x}{2}\right)=r_{2}\left[1-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{2s}{r_{2}}\cos\theta\right)\right]=r_{2}\left[1-\frac{s}{r_{2}}\cos\theta\right],
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies b\approx r_{2}\left[1-\frac{s}{r_{2}}\cos\theta\right]=r_{2}-s\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore r_{2}\approx b+s\cos\theta.
\]

\end_inset

Now, let's move to the potential part: for the inner sphere, the potential
 outside goes as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/r$
\end_inset

, and if the spheres were concentric, then, we know that the contribution
 to the total potential for the external sphere will be constant, but a
 constant given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{2}\sim\frac{1}{b},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the radius of the sphere, then, using the previos result we can state
 that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{2}\sim\frac{1}{r_{2}-s\cos\theta},
\]

\end_inset

and again, if we play a little bit with the math 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{2}\sim\frac{1}{r_{2}}\frac{1}{\left(1-\frac{s}{r_{2}}\cos\theta\right)},
\]

\end_inset

and if we rename 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{s}{r_{2}}\cos\theta$
\end_inset

, then we can Taylor expand as follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{1-x}\approx1+x+\mathcal{O}\left(x^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

then, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{2}\sim\frac{1}{r_{2}}\left(1+\frac{s}{r_{2}}\cos\theta\right).
\]

\end_inset

Now, let's put all the information together:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the inner shell the potential is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{1}=c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{r},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 are determined by the boundary conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the outer shell, the potential is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{2}=\frac{c_{3}}{r}+c_{4}\frac{s}{r^{2}}\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset

but, as we can see when we add the two potentials we'll have two terms that
 go as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/r$
\end_inset

 and therefore, we can incorporate with just one constant.
 But we need two linearly independent solutions, because the PDE that this
 functions satisfy is of second order, then in order to have two solutions,
 we need another solution linearly independent, and, as the problem suggest,
 we can see that if we use 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{2}=c_{3}rs\cos\theta+c_{4}\frac{s}{r^{2}}\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset

then we have a complete solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And with this information, then, the complete solution is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{r}+c_{3}rs\cos\theta+c_{4}\frac{s}{r^{2}}\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\therefore V=c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{r}+s\cos\theta\left(c_{3}r+\frac{c_{4}}{r^{2}}\right).\label{eq:V}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then, the next step is to determine the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 and for that we need, to use the boundary conditions, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(r_{1},\theta\right)=V_{a},\hspace{1em}V\left(r_{2},\theta\right)=V_{b},
\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{a}=V\left(r_{1},\theta\right)=c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{a}+s\cos\theta\left(c_{3}a+\frac{c_{4}}{a^{2}}\right),\label{eq:Va}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and for the other condition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{b}=V\left(r_{2},\theta\right)=c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{b+s\cos\theta}+s\cos\theta\left[c_{3}\left(b+s\cos\theta\right)+\frac{c_{4}}{\left(b+s\cos\theta\right)^{2}}\right],
\]

\end_inset

but, because 
\begin_inset Formula $s\ll b$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{b}=c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{b+s\cos\theta}+c_{3}\left(bs\cos\theta+s^{2}\cos^{2}\theta\right)+\frac{c_{4}s\cos\theta}{\left(b+s\cos\theta\right)^{2}},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies V_{b}\approx c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{b+s\cos\theta}+c_{3}bs\cos\theta+\frac{c_{4}s\cos\theta}{\left(b+s\cos\theta\right)^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

in which I've droped the terms with 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2}$
\end_inset

, and on the other hand, we can rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{b+s\cos\theta}=\frac{1}{b\left(1+x\right)},\hspace{1em}x=\frac{s}{b}\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{\left(b+s\cos\theta\right)^{2}}=\frac{1}{b^{2}\left(1+x\right)^{2}},\hspace{1em}x=\frac{s}{b}\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset

and then, we can Taylor expand using 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{1+x}\approx1-x+\mathcal{Q}\left(x^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{\left(1+x\right)^{2}}\approx1-2x+\mathcal{Q}\left(x^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

then, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{b\left(1+x\right)}\approx\frac{1}{b}\left(1-\frac{s}{b}\cos\theta\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{b^{2}\left(1+x\right)^{2}}\approx\frac{1}{b^{2}}\left(1-\frac{2s}{b}\cos\theta\right),
\]

\end_inset

and then, the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{b}$
\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{b}\approx c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{b}\left(1-\frac{s}{b}\cos\theta\right)+c_{3}bs\cos\theta+\frac{c_{4}s\cos\theta}{b^{2}}\left(1-\frac{2s}{b}\cos\theta\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies V_{b}\approx c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{b}-c_{2}\frac{s}{b^{2}}\cos\theta+c_{3}bs\cos\theta+\frac{c_{4}s\cos\theta}{b^{2}}-2c_{4}\frac{c_{4}s^{2}\cos^{2}\theta}{b^{3}},
\]

\end_inset

and, again, if we drop terms with 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{b}\approx c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{b}-c_{2}\frac{s}{b^{2}}\cos\theta+c_{3}bs\cos\theta+\frac{c_{4}s\cos\theta}{b^{2}},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\implies V_{b}\approx c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{b}+s\cos\theta\left(c_{3}b+\frac{c_{4}}{b^{2}}-\frac{c_{2}}{b^{2}}\right).\label{eq:Vb}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now, with this information we're ready to find the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

, and for that first, we need to realize that both 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{b}$
\end_inset

 are constante, i.e, indepdent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, thus in the equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Va"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Vb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 the terms inside the parenthesis must vanish, ans this give us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{3}r+\frac{c_{4}}{r^{2}}=0\implies c_{3}=-\frac{c_{4}}{a^{3}},
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{3}b+\frac{c_{4}}{b^{2}}-\frac{c_{2}}{b^{2}}=0\implies c_{4}-c_{2}=-c_{3}b^{3},
\]

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{4}=-c_{3}a^{3}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-c_{3}a^{3}-c_{2}=-c_{3}b^{3}\implies c_{2}=c_{3}\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{2}=c_{3}\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right),\hspace{1em}c_{3}=-\frac{c_{4}}{a^{3}}.\label{eq:C2-C3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now, let's perform 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{a}-V_{b}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{a}-V_{b}=c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{a}-\left(c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{b}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies V_{a}-V_{b}=\frac{c_{2}}{a}-\frac{c_{2}}{b}=c_{2}\left(\frac{1}{a}-\frac{1}{b}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies V_{a}-V_{b}=c_{2}\frac{b-a}{ba},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore c_{2}=\frac{ba}{b-a}\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right),
\]

\end_inset

but using the relations in the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:C2-C3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{ba}{b-a}\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)=c_{3}\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)\implies\frac{ba}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)=c_{3},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore c_{3}=\frac{ba}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{ba}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)=-\frac{c_{4}}{a^{3}}\implies\frac{ba^{4}}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)=-c_{4},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore c_{4}=-\frac{ba^{4}}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right),
\]

\end_inset

thus, the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2},c_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{4}$
\end_inset

 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{2}=\frac{ba\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)}{b-a},\hspace{1em}c_{3}=\frac{ba\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)},\hspace{1em}c_{4}=-\frac{ba^{4}\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\label{eq:C1-C3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

And now, in order to calculate the charge on the surface of the inner shell
 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma\left(\theta\right)=\left.-\epsilon_{0}\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}\right|_{a},
\]

\end_inset

then, taking the derivative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 to the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:V"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}=\frac{\partial}{\partial r}\left[c_{1}+\frac{c_{2}}{r}+s\cos\theta\left(c_{3}r+\frac{c_{4}}{r^{2}}\right)\right],
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}=-\frac{c_{2}}{r^{2}}+c_{3}s\cos\theta-2\frac{c_{4}}{r^{3}}s\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}\right|_{a}=-\frac{c_{2}}{a^{2}}+c_{3}s\cos\theta-2\frac{c_{4}}{a^{3}}s\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset

and using the expressions for the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 given in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:C1-C3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}\right|_{a}=-\frac{1}{a^{2}}\left[\frac{ba\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)}{b-a}\right]+\left[\frac{ba\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\right]s\cos\theta-\frac{2}{a^{3}}\left[-\frac{ba^{4}\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\right]s\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\left.\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}\right|_{a}=-\frac{1}{a^{2}}\left[\frac{ba\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)}{b-a}\right]+\left[\frac{ba\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\right]s\cos\theta-2\left[-\frac{ba\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\right]s\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\left.\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}\right|_{a}=-\frac{1}{a^{2}}\left[\frac{ba\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)}{b-a}\right]+\left\{ \left[\frac{ba\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\right]+2\left[\frac{ba\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)}{\left(b-a\right)\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\right]\right\} s\cos\theta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\left.\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}\right|_{a}=\frac{ba\left(V_{a}-V_{b}\right)}{b-a}\left[-\frac{1}{a^{2}}+\frac{3s\cos\theta}{\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\right],
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\left.\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}\right|_{a}=\frac{ba\left(V_{b}-V_{a}\right)}{b-a}\left[\frac{1}{a^{2}}-\frac{3s\cos\theta}{\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\right],
\]

\end_inset

and defining 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}=V_{b}-V_{a}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.\frac{\partial V}{\partial r}\right|_{a}=-\frac{baV_{0}}{b-a}\left[\frac{1}{a^{2}}-\frac{3s\cos\theta}{\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\right],
\]

\end_inset

and finnaly, the charge will be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma\left(\theta\right)=\epsilon_{0}\frac{baV_{0}}{b-a}\left[\frac{1}{a^{2}}-\frac{3s\cos\theta}{\left(b^{3}-a^{3}\right)}\right],
\]

\end_inset

just as we wanted to prove.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
